<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-07-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-07-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="557" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d557">
                    <head>No. 558.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Davis</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Wallace</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg></opener>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-07-10"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 10,
                            1883</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 100.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: * * * Your dispatch No. 234, of June 18,
                        reporting the particulars of the flagrant attempt upon the lives of the Rev.
                        Mr. Knapp and Dr. G. C. Reynolds, by Koords, near Bitlis, has been
                        received.</p>
                    <p>Your action in the premises is approved, and it is trusted that the offenders
                        will be secured and properly punished. You will convey the Department’s
                        thanks to Mr. Wyndham, Her Majesty’s representative at Constantinople, for
                        his courteous assistance through the British consul at Erzroom in the matter
                        of the complaint of the assaulted gentlemen.</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>JOHN DAVIS,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting
                            Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>